  "diary": "Woke up early enough to avoid the transit strike chaos—lucked out driving straight to Building 99. The morning flew by; crushed through a nasty debugging session that's been bugging me all week. Grabbed lunch with the team in the cafeteria, and somehow we ended up talking about weekend plans instead of work, which was nice. Afternoon was a blur of meetings and more code reviews, but I left feeling like I actually shipped something meaningful. The strike was over by the time I headed home, but my car was faster anyway. Made a simple dinner and couldn't resist taking a walk downtown—68 degrees is rare enough that I had to get outside. The weather just hit different today. Came back, chatted with friends online, played some game highlights. Feeling calm, accomplished, and grateful the day didn't get derailed by transit issues.",
  "thought_process": "I woke with the transit strike in the back of my mind, but having a car meant I could bypass all that frustration. The morning code review momentum carried me through; I was in flow state. Lunch felt like a mental break—I actually needed that social reset. The afternoon was heavy with meetings, but I didn't let it drag me down because I knew I'd crushed the morning. Driving home early felt like a win. The weather pulled me outside; partly cloudy and mild is the perfect excuse to walk and decompress. I think the strike, ironically, made my day feel simpler—no transit anxiety meant I could focus on work and then actually enjoy the evening. By the time I got home, I was relaxed enough to just exist without overthinking.",
